Description:
Blood on the Clocktower

Friday, April 26

7pm start (we suggest arriving a few minutes early!)


For adults ages 18+


Who needs candlelight when you've got Blood on the Clocktower? Join for an evening of murder and mystery, where alliances form, secrets unravel, and the fate of the village hangs in the balance!


Blood on the Clocktower is for five-to-twenty courageous players and one devious storyteller, where logic and lies, deduction and deception are used in a thrilling social deduction game. This is currently the top-ranked Party Game on boardgamegeek.com.


You will be randomly assigned as part of the "good" or "evil" team with a particular role. Good players share information to solve the mystery whilst evil players lie about who they are and what they know. The good team wins if they can piece together their knowledge, trust each other, and execute the demon. The evil team wins if the demon can sow distrust, evade detection, and wipe out the village.


Please feel free to bring along snacks and non-alcoholic beverages of your choice, as we do not serve food/drinks on site.


Note that this is not intended as a role-playing game. You don't have to "play" the role you are assigned, although you are welcome to if you so desire! The game works well even if some folks like to role-play and others are more comfortable just being themselves! This game is similar to Mafia, One Night Ultimate Werewolf, or Resistance Avalon.

Board Game Meet-up

Saturday, June 15

6:30-10:30pm

Ages 18+


Pull up a chair and join us for an evening of fun and connection! Our Board Game Meet-up is all about meeting new friends and sharing some laughs over some games.


Our team will select their favourite games to get conversations and laughter going. We'll have quick-playing games and party games set up so that you can move around the room and try different games, while connecting with others.


This meetup is perfect for you if you're keen to expand your social circle and are searching for like-minded tabletop game fans in Squamish to connect with, you want to learn some new party games, or you just want to have some good old-fashioned fun!


Please feel free to bring along snacks and non-alcoholic beverages of your choice, as we don't yet have food/drinks on site.


If you are interested in playing more strategic or serious/longer games, consider joining us for a Board Game Night. Board Game Nights are more about sitting down at a table with your friends, and playing through a game that takes more focus or trying out some of our games that you've been itching to try.


Reserve your spot by purchasing your ticket now. Walk-ins are welcome, and will be granted on a first-come, first-served basis.

Board Game Night

Saturday, June 1

6:30-10:30pm


Gather your friends for a night of focused game play in our Games Room! At our Board Game Night, the games room is open for groups of friends to come in and enjoy a night of uninterrupted gaming fun.


Flying solo and looking for a group of gamers to join? We'll have signs on the tables indicating which tables are open to having other players join them. Show up on time to get in on a game.


Groups can bring their own games or choose from our ever expanding collection. We have games of various themes, styles of gameplay, and for all skill levels.


With comfortable seating, ample table space, and a relaxed atmosphere, Arrow Wood Games provides a great setting to immerse yourselves in your favourite board games. Description:
Camp Arrow Wood

August 26-30

9am-4pm

Ages 6-12*


Calling all young adventurers, aged 6-12*! 


Join us this summer for an unforgettable experience at Camp Arrow Wood! Kids will participate in a mix of games, arts and crafts, and outdoor excursions. We’ll spark imaginations, laugh a lot, learn new things without realizing it, and even get kids moving outdoors.


Kids will do a mix of activities where sometimes they’ll be split into different age groups to provide tailored, age appropriate activities. Sometimes the group will be all together where older kids can develop leadership skills under the mentorship of our staff, while the younger kids will have some great role models to help them through more advanced game play.


Dress for outdoor adventures, and bring snacks, lunch (for full day camps), and water bottles. Kids into Pokémon, or who have other favourite games that they want to share with the group, are welcome to bring them!


Sample schedule for full-day camps:

9:00 am Drop-off, welcome, unstructured play

9:15 am Activity block #1

10:15 am Morning snack

10:30 am Activity block #2

12:00 pm Supervised lunch, unstructured play

1:00 pm Welcome afternoon campers

1:15 pm Outdoor excursion (game-related!) or indoor activity

2:30 pm Afternoon snack

2:45pm Activity block #3

3:45 pm Clean up

4:00 pm Pick-up


Activity blocks will be a mix of games and game-related activities. Games could include board games, card games, role-playing games, party games. Game-related activities could include designing games, painting miniatures, live action role-playing, improv, puzzles, and more.


Feel free to drop off your kids up to 5 minutes before the start time and pick them up 5 minutes after the finish time if you need to. Outside of this grace window, we have a firm late fee policy aimed at ensuring our staff can prepare for other events or get home to their own families after work. You can find the policy in the FAQs on our website.


* Kids aged 5 are welcome to join if they have completed kindergarten.

Description:
Collaboration Day Afternoon Camp

Wednesday, April 17

12:00-3:00pm

For kids in kindergarten to grade 4


Wednesday April 17th is Collaboration Day at Squamish Elementary, which means kids are dismissed at noon. This can leave parents in a tight spot, so we've created an afternoon camp just for Squamish Elementary kids!


We'll meet the kids at Squamish Elementary at noon and walk them back over to Arrow Wood Games* for an afternoon of fun and games. Activities will include a mix of board games, card games, Pokémon, puzzles, crafts, role playing games, and more, depending on the interests of the kids.


Kids should pack their lunches, snacks, water bottles, clothing appropriate for the weather, and, if they are into Pokémon, their Pokémon cards.


*Kids will need a waiver for this camp signed at least 24 hours before the camp in order to be picked up from the school. We'll email you the waiver after you've registered.


PLEASE NOTE: this is a program offered by Arrow Wood Games, and not a program offered through or by Squamish Elementary School and is not publicly funded. Squamish Elementary has kindly let parents know about it through their newsletter.


We offer a 10% siblings discount for those of you who have more than one child joining the camp! Email us info@arrowwoodgames.com before registering and we'll get you set up with the discount.

Description:
Dungeons & Dragons Adventure Guild

August 6-9

9am-4pm

Ages 8-12


Is your 8-12 year old an experienced Dungeons & Dragons player, or do they want to learn the game? This one-of-a-kind camp is for them!


At the D&D Adventurer’s Guild Camp, every day will be jam-packed with all things D&D. Each day will include at least 2 hours of playing in a campaign that will span the week. Other activities will include things like drawing adventure maps, crafting props and terrain, designing new monsters, painting miniatures, further developing their characters, improv activities to help build roleplaying skills, and so much more… and maybe even some live action roleplay (LARPing)!


Dress for outdoor adventures, and bring snacks, lunch (for full day camps), and water bottles. Kids who have any D&D-related props, books, characters, art, or anything else that they want to share with the group are encouraged to bring them, and are responsible for taking care and keeping track of them. Arrow Wood Games is not responsible for any lost or stolen items.


While the day’s schedule will vary as we have so many activities to fit in, here is what a sample day’s schedule looks like:

9:00 am Drop-off, unstructured time

9:15 am Campaign - D&D game time with some warm up activities to get the creative juices flowing!

10:30 am Morning snack

10:45 am More D&D!

12:00 pm Lunch break and unstructured time

1:00 pm Outdoor excursion: Improv activities for role playing at the park

2:30 pm Miniature painting

3:45 pm Clean up and wrap up

4:00 pm Pick-up


No experience necessary. Kids may bring their own level 1-3 character and dice, or, if they are new, can use one of our pre-made characters and dice.


Feel free to drop off your kids up to 5 minutes before the start time and pick them up 5 minutes after the finish time if you need to. Outside of this grace window, we have a firm late fee policy aimed at ensuring our staff can prepare for other events or get home to their own families after work. You can find the policy in the FAQs on our website.

January 9 - February 6 (5 weeks)


Experience required! 


Players should come with a level 1, 2 or 3 character built following the standard rules, or may play with a premade character that we will have ready for them. Bring your own dice.


D&D is a role-playing game where players take on the role of adventurers in a fantasy world - they embark on quests, solve problems, and defeat villains. One person, called the Game Master, guides the story and sets the challenges (that’s us!) 


(TIP FOR PARENTS: D&D has kids learning & practicing a ton of life skills without them even being aware of it!)


This program is for kids who have had some experience playing D&D. If your child has not played before, contact us about having them join one of our introductory sessions.


We are limiting the group size to 6 kids, so don't delay on signing up so that your kids can be one of the few adventurers in the world of the Arrow Wood!

D&D Dungeon Master Academy

August 19-23

9am-12pm

Ages 8-12


If your kid is interested in or is already leading Dungeons & Dragons campaigns for their friends or family, this is the camp for them! In the Dungeon Masters Academy kids will learn the ropes of how to lead their friends on epic quests. 


Experience playing D&D required. Experience as a Dungeon Master is optional. If your child has not played D&D before, consider joining us for one of our D&D Adventure Guild Camps or one of our regularly scheduled Learn to Play: Intro Adventures.


Things we will cover include: 

  • World building
  • Campaign development
  • Encounter design
  • The physical elements of D&D (props, maps, etc.)
  • Creating and playing memorable non-player characters (NPCs)
  • Improv skills, game mechanics
  • Session management (e.g., how to control timing and group dynamics)


Aspiring dungeon masters will also get a chance to practice their skills during the week! Each participant will run a mini adventure for their peers, and will receive positive and constructive feedback from the staff and other players - we’ll guide them on how to give feedback.


Feel free to drop off your kids up to 5 minutes before the start time and pick them up 5 minutes after the finish time if you need to. Outside of this grace window, we have a firm late fee policy aimed at ensuring our staff can prepare for other events or get home to their own families after work. You can find the policy on the FAQs on our website.

D&D: Epic Battles

August 19-23

1-4pm

Ages 8-12


Join us for this half-day camp, where each day kids will battle it out with a new big baddie! This is not a normal campaign - each day is a standalone boss fight!


No experience required! This program is great for kids with or without experience playing D&D.


Kids should know that this is a week where their character might die, so we encourage them to create “disposable” characters or use some of the premade characters we have ready to go in store. If your child likes in-game combat (or generally to smash things when they’re playing D&D), this camp would be a great fit for them.


Players should come ready with a level 1, 2 or 3 character built following the standard rules, or may play with a premade character that we will have ready for them. They should bring their own dice, or can borrow some of ours.


D&D is a role-playing game where players take on the role of adventurers in a fantasy world - they embark on quests, solve problems, and defeat villains. But... in this camp... it's just defeating villains. Big, bad villains.

Ages 6-9

January 10 - February 7 (5 weeks)


What happens when your town is in trouble, and the adults are away? Hero Kids save the day! 


Hero Kids is a fantasy role playing game (like Dungeons & Dragons) designed for kids. Young heroes embark on exciting adventures, solving mysteries, rescuing magical creatures, battling monsters, and generally saving the day. With a lot of laughter, creativity, collaboration, and teamwork.


Our experienced Game Master (GM) will lead the kids through the quests, while ensuring each child is creatively engaged in play and interacting with the group. No experience necessary.


Instructor ratio is 6:1.

Hero Kids is a fantasy role playing game (like Dungeons & Dragons) designed for kids. Young heroes embark on exciting adventures, solving mysteries, rescuing magical creatures, battling monsters, and generally saving the day. With a lot of laughter, creativity, collaboration, and teamwork.


Our experienced Game Master (GM) will leading the kids through the quests, while ensuring each child is creatively engaged in play and interacting with the group.

Description:
Spring Break Learn to Play D&D

Ages 10-14

March 19, 20, 21

1-3pm


This Learn to Play Dungeons & Dragons will teach kids the rules of the game, and they will also embark upon an exciting adventure! Bonus: after they complete this program they'll be able to sign up for our after-school and other programs that require experience.


D&D is a role playing role-playing game where players take on the role of adventurers in a fantasy world - they embark on quests, solve problems, and defeat villains. One person, called the Game Master, guides the story and sets the challenges (that’s us!)


(TIP FOR PARENTS: D&D has kids learning & practicing a ton of life skills without them even being aware of it!)


This program is for those who haven't played Dungeons and Dragons before, or who have very little experience.


We are limiting the group size to 6 kids, so don't delay on signing up so that your kids can be one of the few adventurers in the world of the Arrow Wood!

Learn to Play D&D: Character Creation

Saturday, February 3

4:00-6:00pm


Do you want to play Dungeons & Dragons but don't know where to start? Let us teach you some of the rules of the world’s greatest roleplaying game by helping you create your first character!


Learn to Play D&D: Character Creation is meant to be a one-time primer before joining one of our upcoming D&D games or getting started with your friends. One of our professional Game Masters will guide you through the character creation process, and show you different ways to customize your hero so they’re ready for any adventure.


This two-hour D&D event is hosted in our games room by one our Game Masters. This is a mixed age event for players 8 and up, and families are encouraged to attend. Players ages 8-13 must be accompanied by a participating (paying & playing) adult.


Please bring your own set of dice, and arrive on time.


Note: you do not need to have played D&D previously to attend this workshop. However, players may find that attending our Introductory Adventure helpful before attending this.


Maximum 6 players, register early.

Ready to try your first game of Dungeons & Dragons?

Saturday, February 3

12:30-3:00pm


Are you ready to try your first game of Dungeons & Dragons? Join us on a short adventure where we'll show you the ropes!


Learn to Play D&D: Introductory Adventure is meant to be a one-time primer to get some experience before joining our upcoming D&D campaigns. One of our Game Masters will guide you through the rules in various scenes that highlight the three pillars of Dungeons & Dragons – Social Encounters, Exploration and Combat.


This 2.5-hour session is a mixed-age event for players 8 and up, and families are encouraged to attend. Players ages 8-13 must be accompanied by a participating (paying and playing) adult.


Please arrive on time! Pre-registrations are highly recommended but walk-ins are welcome. Space is limited and will be granted on a first-come, first served basis.


Note: you do not need to come to this adventure with a character - we will have one ready for you. But feel free to bring one if you have one from our character creation workshop!


Maximum 6 players per group.

New Years Board Game Extravaganza - Ages 10-14
Description:
Board Game Extravaganza

Ages 10-14

Wednesday, January 3

11am-1pm


Unleash the joy of games at our Board Game Extravaganza!


For 2 hours, our dynamic staff will guide kids through an array of age appropriate games. From classic favourites to exciting new challenges.


Discover the thrill of strategy, the excitement of competition, and the camaraderie of shared victories. Let the games begin!


Instructor ratio is 10:1.

Item Name: New Years Board Game Extravaganza - Ages 6-9
Description:
Board Game Extravaganza

Ages 6-9

Wednesday, January 3

9-10:30am


Unleash the joy of games at our Board Game Extravaganza!


For 1.5 hours, our dynamic staff will guide kids through an array of age appropriate games. From classic favourites to exciting new challenges.


Discover the thrill of strategy, the excitement of competition, and the camaraderie of shared victories. Let the games begin!


Instructor ratio is 8:1.

D&D Adventure

Ages 10-14

January 3, 4 and 5

1-3pm


Experience required. If your child has not played before, consider joining our Learn to Play D&D program on Tuesday, January 2 to set them up for this session!


This D&D adventure will take place over three 2-hour sessions the week before school goes back.


Players should come ready with a level 1, 2 or 3 character built following the standard rules, or may play with a premade character that we will have ready for them. Bring your own dice.


D&D is a role-playing game where players take on the role of adventurers in a fantasy world - they embark on quests, solve problems, and defeat villains. One person, called the Game Master, guides the story and sets the challenges (that’s us!) 


(TIP FOR PARENTS: D&D has kids learning & practicing a ton of life skills without them even being aware of it!)


Instructor ratio is 6:1.

D&D Adventure

Ages 13-18

January 3, 4 and 5

3:30-5:30pm

Item Name: New Years D&D One-Shot (Adults) - Kobold Alone
Description:
Join us for our very first Arrow Wood one-shot adventure for adults!


This is 3-4 hour D&D adventure for players experienced with the basic mechanics of D&D 5e and creating their own character. Character creation guidelines will be emailed to players after registration.


Players should come ready with a level 1, 2 or 3 character built following the standard rules, or may play with a premade character that we will have ready for them. Bring your own dice.


The hook:

Through the grapevine, your party has learned that there's a manor house on the southern part of town that's ripe for the picking. Some believe that the people who own the house - who've just taken a lavish, winter holiday trip to a foreign land - are people of disreputable value. In fact, rumour has it that the lord of the manor has ties to the criminal underworld; how else can he afford such a nice house with so many kids? The lord's name is Peter McCallister. However, there's one catch: supposedly, a crafty little kobold has snuck into the place and made it his own while the McCallisters are away.


Ages: 18+

Start: 6pm. Please arrive on time.

Max: 5 players

Item Name: New Years Learn to Play D&D: Introductory Adventure (ages 8+)
Description:
Ready to try your first game of Dungeons & Dragons?

January 2

2:00pm - 5:00pm


Are you ready to try your first game of Dungeons & Dragons? Join us on a short adventure where we'll show you the ropes!


Learn to Play D&D: Introductory Adventure is meant to be a one-time primer to get some experience before joining our upcoming D&D campaigns. One of our Game Masters will guide you through the rules in various scenes that highlight the three pillars of Dungeons & Dragons – Social Encounters, Exploration and Combat.


This three-hour session is a mixed-age event for players 8 and up, and families are encouraged to attend. Players ages 8-13 must be accompanied by a participating adult.


Please arrive on time! Pre-registrations are appreciated but walk-ins are welcome. Space is limited and will be granted on a first-come, first served basis.


Maximum 6 players per group.

January 2

6:00pm - 9:00pm

One of our Game Masters will guide you through the rules in various scenes that highlight the three pillars of Dungeons & Dragons – Social Encounters, Exploration and Combat.


Please arrive on time! Pre-registrations are appreciated but walk-ins are welcome. Space is limited and will be granted on a first-come, first served basis. We cannot reserve your space without payment.

Item Name: New Years Learn to Play Pokémon - Ages 10-14
Description:
Learn to Play Pokémon

Ages 10-14

Friday, January 5

11am-1pm


Does your child have a collection of Pokémon cards but doesn't know what to do with them? Or get some cards as gifts this holiday season?


Pokémon is a collectible trading card game, and we think it's super fun! So let's put those Pokémon cards to good use!


Kids can bring their own cards, or borrow a deck from us, and learn to play! No experience necessary, though those with experience are also welcome to join in the Pokémon fun!


Instructor ratio is 6:1.

Magical Kitties Save the Day!

Ages 10-14

Thursday, January 4

11am-1pm


Suitable for kids who love cats, magic, and saving the day! No experience necessary.


In this role-playing game, each player takes on the role of a magical kitty with unique powers and abilities. The setting is a world where magical kitties secretly protect their humans and their hometown from various threats, such as magical storms, devious villains, and other dangers.


The game emphasizes cooperative storytelling, allowing players to use their kitty characters' magical abilities to overcome challenges and solve problems. It encourages creativity, teamwork, and imaginative play.


Instructor ratio is 8:1.

Magical Kitties Save the Day!

Ages 6-9

Thursday, January 4

9-10:30am


Suitable for kids who love cats, magic, and saving the day! No experience necessary.


In this role-playing game, each player takes on the role of a magical kitty with unique powers and abilities. The setting is a world where magical kitties secretly protect their humans and their hometown from various threats, such as magical storms, devious villains, and other dangers.


We will specifically tailor this program to our younger players. The game emphasizes cooperative storytelling, allowing players to use their kitty characters' magical abilities to overcome challenges and solve problems. It encourages creativity, teamwork, and imaginative play.


Instructor ratio is 8:1.

Item Name: New Years Pokémon Trade & Play - Ages 6-9

Pokémon Trade & Play

Ages 6-9

Friday, January 5

9-10:30am


Does your kid love Pokémon and/or have a bunch of cards that they don't know what to do with? Did they get some Pokémon cards as a gift and can't stop talking about them?


Have them join us for some active, social Pokémon fun! They can bring their own cards, and we will also have decks to loan out.


No experience necessary for this light introduction to the trading card game. We'll talk about the basics of the cards and creatures, and have some Pokémon-related activities.


Instructor ratio is 6:1.

Dungeons & Dragons: One-Shot Adventure (Pro-D Day)

Ages 10-14

Friday January 26, 1-3pm


Experience required! 


Players should come with a level 1, 2 or 3 character built following the standard rules, or may play with a premade character that we will have ready for them. Bring your own dice.


D&D is a role-playing game where players take on the role of adventurers in a fantasy world - they embark on quests, solve problems, and defeat villains. One person, called the Game Master, guides the story and sets the challenges (that’s us!) 


(TIP FOR PARENTS: D&D has kids learning & practicing a ton of life skills without them even being aware of it!)


This program is for kids who have had some experience playing D&D. If your child has not played before, contact us about having them join one of our introductory sessions.


We are limiting the group size to 6 kids, so don't delay on signing up so that your kids can be one of the few adventurers in this Arrow Wood one-shot Pro-D Day adventure!

Description:
Spring Break Pokémon Trade & Play!

Ages 10-14

Friday, March 22

11am-12:30


Does your kid love Pokémon and/or have a bunch of cards that they don't know what to do with?


Pokémon is a collectible trading card game, and we think it's super fun! So let's put those Pokémon cards to good use!


Kids can bring their own cards, or borrow a deck from us, and learn to play! No experience necessary, though those with experience are also welcome to join in the Pokémon fun!

Spring Break Pokémon Trade & Play!

Ages 6-9

Friday, March 22

9-10:30am


Does your kid love Pokémon and/or have a bunch of cards that they don't know what to do with?


Have them join us for some active, social Pokémon fun! They can bring their own cards, and we will also have decks to loan out.


No experience necessary for this light introduction to the trading card game. We'll talk about the basics of the cards and creatures, have some Pokémon-related activities, and those who are ready to play can battle it out!

Warhammer Game Night

Friday, July 5

Starts at 7pm


Once a month on Fridays, join us for a night of Warhammer. Bring your armies and friends, check out the action, have fun, and get your game on!


The main event is a Kill Team Summer League that is being organized by the local Warhammer community. But other players are also welcome to come and grab a table to play other games like Warcry or Necromunda.


Feel free to stop by during any game night and chat with the group and leaders. Since space is limited and this is a very popular night, we recommend either meeting the group a week ahead of your first game, or touching base with them through their Discord group to help make table arrangements and pairings smooth. However, drop ins are welcomed and this group has a reputation for being very inclusive and having a desire to build the local Warhammer community.


Please feel free to bring along snacks and non-alcoholic beverages of your choice, as we do not currently serve food/drinks on site.


Reserve your spot by purchasing your ticket now. Walk-ins are welcome, and will be granted on a first-come, first-served basis.
